{{Infobox artwork | image_file=Tom Roberts - Coming South - Google Art Project.jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=300px | title=Coming South | artist=[[Tom Roberts]] | year=[[1886 in art|1886]] | medium=oil on canvas | height_metric=63.5 | width_metric= 52.2 | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Melbourne]] | museum=[[National Gallery of Victoria]] }} '''''Coming South''''' is a [[1886 in art|1886]] painting by the Australian artist [[Tom Roberts]]. The painting depicts migrants coming to Australia from Europe aboard a steamship. Roberts based the painting on sketches he had made when returning to Australia aboard the ''SS Lusitania'' in 1885 after four years abroad in Europe.<ref name="Migration">{{cite web | url=http://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/collection/stories/identity/cultural-and-personal-identity/migration-and-multiculturalism | title=Migration and multiculturalism | publisher=National Gallery of Victoria | work=Collection Stories | accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref>
Historian [[Humphrey McQueen]] describes ''Coming South'' as one of Roberts' seven best-known paintings.<ref name="McQueen">{{cite web | url=http://home.alphalink.com.au/~loge27/roberts/roberts_roberts_review.htm | title=Review: Tom Roberts | accessdate=11 May 2012 | author=Seeton, Alexander}}</ref> The [[National Gallery of Victoria]] describes it as "a definitive image of the migrant experience" and "Roberts's first exploration of one of the great themes of Australian life".<ref name="NGV">{{cite web | url=http://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/col/work/2892 | title=Coming South | publisher=National Gallery of Victoria | work=Collection Online | accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref>
The painting was acquired by the National Gallery of Victoria in 1967.<ref name="NGV" />
